Problem Set 3

Gov 1005 Spring 2020

Read how we grade problem sets.

Objectives for this problem set:

  • Students will apply the Rubin Causal Model to example data
  • Students will develop skills for manipulating strings and factor variables
  • Students will demonstrate their ability to retrieve data from multiple sources (csv, wikipedia)

Getting Data Into R

Were going to use some data from ``Bread and Circuses: Sports and Public Opinion in China, which attempts to understand whether sports can increase the favorable attitudes of citizens toward their government. The authors recruited survey participants in two Chinese cities to answer questions about their satisfaction with the government. The treatment group watched a 2 minute video about Chinese athletes succeeding in the international arena before answering the questions.

  1. First, create a subdirectory in your project called raw-data. Notice that this repo contains the spreadsheet xian_data.csv. Move this in yourraw-data subdirectory. (Remember to push and commit these changes!)

  2. Read in your csv using read_csv. Make sure to clean your data. For example, make te colimn names easy to work with, as we did in class. Set the undefined and missing values as NA.

Madlibs

  1. X respondents are in the treatment group.

  2. Among respondents from the treatment group, the government has an average X rating.

  3. The most common rating for the governments handling of traffic is X.

  4. X respondents have given the government a 10 rating overall or on demolitions or on traffic.

  5. But only X gave the government a 10 rating overall and on demolitions and on traffic.

The variable news_source asks respondents to list which news sources they get their news from. Some respondents answered more than one option, so their answer lists a number of letters together. A means Television, B means Newspapers, C means Radio, etc

  1. The number of respondents who get their news from Television is X

  2. Of the 4 different locations where the respondents were surveyed, the following two locations end with square: X,X
